import { useState } from "react";

function App() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <>
      <h1>{count}</h1>

      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
        Increase
      </button>
    </>
  );
}

export default App;


How It Works

Initial:

count = 0

Click:

count + 1

Result:

1

Click again:

2

And so on.

Problem: Multiple Updates

Consider:

setCount(count + 1);
setCount(count + 1);

Expected:

+2

Actual:

+1

Why?

Because React batches updates.

Both lines use the same old value.



Solution: Functional Updates

Use:

setCount(prev => prev + 1);
Syntax
setCount(previousValue => {
    return previousValue + 1;
});

Short form:

setCount(prev => prev + 1);


Line by Line Explanation
prev => prev + 1
prev

Previous state value.

Example:

prev = 5
prev + 1

Returns:

6

React stores 6.

Example
setCount(prev => prev + 1);
setCount(prev => prev + 1);

Result:

0 → 1 → 2

Now it correctly increases by 2.



Visual Flow
count = 0

First Update
0 + 1 = 1

Second Update
1 + 1 = 2

Final Value = 2
Real World Example

Shopping Cart

const [items, setItems] = useState(0);

function addItem() {
  setItems(prev => prev + 1);
}

Every click adds one item.



Multiple State Variables

A component can have many states.

Example:

const [name, setName] = useState("");
const [age, setAge] = useState(20);
const [city, setCity] = useState("Bangalore");
Why?

Different data should have separate states.

Example:

Name
Age
Email
Phone

Each changes independently.


Example
import { useState } from "react";

function App() {

  const [name, setName] = useState("");
  const [age, setAge] = useState(20);

  return (
    <>
      <h2>Name: {name}</h2>
      <h2>Age: {age}</h2>

      <button onClick={() => setName("Ithesh")}>
        Set Name
      </button>

      <button onClick={() => setAge(age + 1)}>
        Increase Age
      </button>
    </>
  );
}

export default App;
