State Best Practices
Good
const [name, setName] = useState("");
const [email, setEmail] = useState("");

Separate state.

Bad
const [everything, setEverything] = useState();

Too vague.


Common Mistakes
Mistake 1

Direct modification

❌

count = count + 1;

Correct:

setCount(count + 1);


Mistake 2

Updating twice

❌

setCount(count + 1);
setCount(count + 1);

Correct:

setCount(prev => prev + 1);
setCount(prev => prev + 1);


Mistake 3

Forgetting initial value

❌

useState();

Better:

useState("");

or

useState(0);


Industry Example

Login Form

const [email, setEmail] = useState("");
const [password, setPassword] = useState("");
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

Each state controls a specific feature.

This is how real projects are built.


Interview Questions
Q1

What is the difference between:

setCount(count + 1);

and

setCount(prev => prev + 1);
Answer

Functional updates use the latest state value and prevent stale state problems.


Q2

Can a component have multiple states?

Answer

Yes.

const [name, setName] = useState("");
const [age, setAge] = useState(20);


Q3

Does changing state re-render the component?

Answer

Yes.

React updates the UI automatically.

